From Kenneth Gilbert Subject Re Persistent vs Chronic In article David Rind writes In article Horace Enea writes Can anyone out there tell me the difference between a persistent disease and a chronic one For example persistent hepatitis vs chronic I don't think there is a general Rather there are two classes of chronic hepatitis chronic active hepatitis and chronic persistent I can't think of any other disease where the term persistent is used with or in preference to Much as these two terms chronic active and chronic persistent sound fuzzy the actual distinction between the two conditions is often fairly fuzzy as I beg to Chronic active hepatitis implies that the disease remains active and generally leads to liver At the very minimum the patient has persistently elevated liver enzymes what some call transaminitis Chronic persistant hepatitis simply means that the patient has HbSag in his her blood and can transmit the infection but shows no evidence of progressive If I had to choose I'd much rather have the persistant Kenneth Gilbert University of Pittsburgh General Internal Medicine not a programmer